1)Before routing traffic to a pod why do we need to check health  of the pod.

  - 1) Avoid sending traffic to broken pods
    2) Ensure application is fully ready
    3) Prevent downtime (HIGH AVAILABILITY)
2)In a pod how do you going to check helath.
  - Kubernetes uses Probes to check container health
    1) Readiness Probe
          Checks: “Can this pod receive traffic?”
          If fails → pod is removed from service
    2) Liveness Probe
          Checks: “Is this container alive?”
          If fails → container is restarted
    3) Startup Probe (optional)
          For slow-start apps
          Gives time before liveness starts
3)which protocol we need follow which request what reposne we have to get to define or dclare the container is in health status
   - Kubernetes supports 3 ways (protocols):
     1)HTTP (Most Common ⭐) - 👉 Kubernetes sends: --> GET /health-->👉 Expected response:200 OK ✅-->❌ If:500 / timeout → unhealthy

     2) TCP Check--👉 Checks:“Kubernetes checks if port is open(Is port open?)”-->✅ If connection succeeds →healthy or ❌ If not → unhealthy

     3)  Command (Exec)-- 👉 If command:exits 0 → healthy ✅ or exits non-zero → unhealthy ❌ 


